## Math Notation

The KV cache introduces notation for incremental attention during generation:

| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| K^l\_cache, V^l\_cache | Cached key/value tensors for layer l |
| pos | Current write position (number of tokens already cached) |
| Q\_new | Query projection for the new token(s) only |
| K\_new, V\_new | Key/value projections for the new token(s) |
| K\_full = K\_cache\[0:pos+1\] | All cached keys through current position |
| V\_full = V\_cache\[0:pos+1\] | All cached values through current position |

Standard attention applied to the new token:

**Attention(Q\_new, K\_full, V\_full) = softmax(Q\_new · K\_full^T / √d\_k) · V\_full**

Without cache: generate token at position t by recomputing Q, K, V for all t tokens.
With cache: compute only Q\_new, K\_new, V\_new for the 1 new token; read K\_full, V\_full from cache.

## Why KV Cache?

During autoregressive generation, we produce **one token at a time**. Each new token must attend to all previous tokens. This creates a fundamental choice:

**Without cache**: Recompute Q, K, V for the entire sequence from scratch at every step. Attention costs O(t²) at step t. Over n steps, total work is **Σ t² ≈ O(n³)**.

**With cache**: Store K and V from previous steps. Only compute Q, K, V for the single new token. Attention costs O(t) per step (one query row against t cached keys). Over n steps, total work is **Σ t ≈ O(n²)**.

```elixir
data =
  for n <- [10, 20, 30, 50, 75, 100] do
    without = Enum.sum(for t <- 1..n, do: t * t)
    with_cache = Enum.sum(for t <- 1..n, do: t)

    [
      %{"tokens" => n, "operations" => without, "method" => "Without Cache (O(n³))"},
      %{"tokens" => n, "operations" => with_cache, "method" => "With Cache (O(n²))"}
    ]
  end
  |> List.flatten()

Vl.new(width: 500, height: 300, title: "Total Computation: Cached vs Non-Cached Generation")
|> Vl.data_from_values(data)
|> Vl.mark(:bar)
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "tokens", type: :ordinal, title: "Tokens Generated")
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "operations", type: :quantitative, title: "Total Operations (relative)")
|> Vl.encode_field(:color, "method", type: :nominal)
|> Vl.encode_field(:xOffset, "method", type: :nominal)
```

At 100 tokens, the non-cached approach does roughly **50×** more work. The gap widens as sequences grow longer — this is why every production inference system uses KV caching.

## Build a KV Cache

The cache is a simple data structure: pre-allocated tensors for K and V at each transformer layer, plus a position counter.

**Shape per layer**: `{batch_size, max_seq_len, n_kv_heads, head_dim}`

Three operations:
- **new** — allocate zero-filled tensors
- **update** — write new K/V at the current position, advance position counter
- **get_layer** — read K/V tensors for a specific layer

